ding the potential of our becoming in ways that enhance our participation in the creative evolution of life, and she characterizes forms of subjectivity and cultural practice that could support such evolution. By means of her lucid reading taken through the lens of feminist philosophy, Lorraine is not only able to present clearly Deleuze and Guattari's project but also an intriguing elaboration of some of the project's practical implications for novel approaches to contemporary problems in philosophy, feminism, cultural theory, and human living.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDeleuze, Gilles, -- 1925-1995. 0aEthics. 0aFeminist ethics. 0aGuattari, Félix, -- 1930-1992. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Feminist Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Phenomenology. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Post Structuralism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438436647423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438436647/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles